Yes — this complies with SC 2.4.13 *if* the notification does not obscure any other focused component *at the moment focus lands there*.

The source document lists this as a valid example:
> *A notification is implemented as a sticky header and the keyboard focus is moved to the notification. The notification disappears when it loses focus, and does not obscure any other controls (including the focus indicator visible prior to the notification).*

Critical conditions for compliance:
- ✅ The notification must not obscure any focusable component *while* focus is on that component
- ✅ It must not reappear or shift content *after* focus leaves, causing sudden layout shifts that obscure the next focus target
- ✅ The disappearance must be immediate or smoothly transitioned *without* pushing focus targets out of view

Recommended implementation:
```css
/* Ensure the notification doesn’t overlap content when focused */
[role="alert"] {
  position: sticky;
  top: 0;
  z-index: 100;
}
/* When notification is focused, ensure it doesn’t occlude other elements */
[role="alert"]:focus {
  scroll-margin-top: 4rem; /* or sufficient space to prevent overlap */
}
```

If the notification fades out *before* focus reaches subsequent elements (e.g., via `transition: opacity 0.2s ease-out`), ensure no element briefly becomes hidden during the transition. Use `transition-behavior: allow-discrete;` or delay transitions until blur, not focus.

This design passes SC 2.4.13 when the focused component is always fully visible.

