```

Note: This is **not** about user precision — it's about *inclusive design for motor and visual impairments*.

Yes, if the tablist meets all conditions: (1) the group has a focus indicator of sufficient size and contrast (e.g., ≥24px area, ≥3:1 contrast ratio), and (2) the tablist behaves as a *synchronized* component—i.e., activation of any tab immediately updates both the active tab and the panel content.

From the source document:
> *‘Having a focus indicator only around the whole is possible where there is no need to have a selected sub-component while another sub-component has focus… only one tab item can be selected at a time… a separate focus indicator is redundant.’*

In this case, the **group focus indicator must meet the requirements of SC 2.4.10** (not the subcomponent), and visual selection state (e.g., active vs unselected tabs) must satisfy SC 1.4.11 (Non-text Contrast).

Example implementation:
```html
<div role="tablist" aria-label="Document tabs" tabindex="0" class="tablist-focused">
  <div role="tab" aria-selected="true" class="tab active">Details</div>
  <div role="tab" aria-selected="false" class="tab">Versions</div>
</div>
```
With CSS:
```css
.tablist-focused:focus {
  outline: 3px solid #005a9c;
  outline-offset: 2px;
}
.tab.active {
  background: #e6f0fa; /* meets 1.4.11 contrast */
}
.tab:not(.active) {
  background: #f8f9fa;
}
```

⚠️ If tabs are *unsynchronized* (i.e., one tab can be focused while another remains selected), you must also show a subcomponent focus indicator—otherwise SC 2.4.10 fails.
